result.execSummary:
The defendant Tiffany White was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Maintain Drug Trafficking Place, a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.42(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: No reply from surety/defendant.

Defendant Tiffany White in court with attorney James Edgar Toran.  Defendant Tiffany White in custody.  Dennis Patrick Murphy appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: AS. Case calendared for return on warrant, however defense requests sentencing hearing.   Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.  

AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of  3 YEARS with 23 days credit CONSECUTIVE  to any other sentence; the INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 1  YEAR; the MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 2 YEARS. 

Court finds defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration program and the WI Substance Abuse program.

Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on 2 YEARS probation. Court authorizes transfer of probation to any other state, including Michigan.

Conditions of Probation/ Extended Supervision if revoked:
- If revoked, Court leaves conditions of extended supervision to the discretion of the department.
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any programs deemed necessary by the probation department.
- Absolute sobriety.
- DNA sample.
- No possession of controlled substances/alcohol without a valid prescription.
- Random urine screens at least 1 time per month.
- No possession of drug paraphernalia.
- No contact with known illegal drug users/manufacturers/deliverers.
- No contact with known gang members.
- No contact with Josiah G. or Michael R.
- No possession of firearms/ammunition/magazines/holsters/body armor. 
- Cognitive Behavioral Intervention program.
- Complete parenting program.
- Comply with any children or family court orders.
- No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause.

Court ordered the defendant pay all of the following by 2/9/2020.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment:
All mandatory court costs, fees, assessments and surcharges (including DNA); 
If revoked, Court ordered that all court costs, fines, surcharges and/or restitution be paid through collection by the Department of Corrections in an amount or percentage the Department (DOC) determines to be reasonable and as a condition of extended supervision.  DOC shall collect those sums.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.

20 day appeal rights given,
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon she may never possess a firearm. 
Court advised defendant of her right to seek postconviction relief.
Court advised defendant that she may not vote until his civil rights have been restored.

Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing.
